                    "firstName": "Albert S.",
                    "lastName": "Feng"
                }
            ],
            "abstractNote": "Echolocating bats assess target range by the delay in echo relative to the emitted sonar pulse. Earlier studies in FM bats showed that a population of neurons in auditory centers above the inferior colliculus (IC) is tuned to echo delay, with diVerent neurons tuned to diVerent echo delays. A building block for delay-tuned responses is paradoxical latency shift (PLS), featuring longer response latencies to more intense sounds. PLS is Wrst created in the IC, where neurons exhibit unit-speciWc quantum increase in response latency with increasing sound level. Other IC neurons display oscillatory discharges whose period is unitspeciWc and level tolerant, indicating that this is attributable to cell’s intrinsic properties. High-threshold inhibition of oscillatory discharge produces PLS, indicating that oscillatory discharge is a building block for PLS. To investigate the cellular basis of oscillatory discharges, we performed whole-cell patch-clamp recordings from IC neurons in leopard frogs (which also exhibit oscillatory discharges and PLS). These recordings show that IC neurons are heterogeneous displaying diverse biophysical phenotypes; each phenotype (and cell) has its own membrane time constant, input resistance, and strengths of Ih, Ikir, Ikv—these intrinsic properties give rise to cell-speciWc resonance which can be observed through current and aVerent stimulations.",
